Harmonious Co-Existence - International Art Collection from NAMOC, an exhibition featuring masterpieces selected from 61 countries and regions, kicked off at The National Art Museum of China (NAMOC) on Wednesday.Displaying 200 works of art dating from the 19th century to today, the exhibition is divided into six sections: international artworks donated by the famous collecting couple Peter and Irene Ludwig, international oil painting, international printmaking, international sculpture, international photographs and miscellaneous watercolor paintings, sketches and lacquer wares.The Ludwigs donated 117 international artworks to NAMOC in 1996 covering a wide variety of world famous artists, such as Pablo Picasso (1881-1973), Salvador Dali (1904-89), Kaethe Kollwitz (1867-1945) and Katsushika Hokusai ((1760-1849)."I am an artist myself," Li Ran, a visitor wandering Hall 1, told the Global Times. "I do traditional Chinese ink paintings, but I find inspiration in these Western oil paintings as well."The exhibition comes to an end on July 8. Backgrounder: the AIIB explainedImpact of anti-corruption campaignBig changes in China's top military brass Australia's paranoia over China smacks of racismBoy band EXO appointed as honorary ambassador for S. Korean tourism UN chief appoints Australian to lead reform of UN development system World Cup should not be used for political endsUS court upholds travel banThe Color Run How To Say Love To A Chinese Girl

